defaultWe have two issues to raise here.  Firstly, the obvious mechanism and which is now being actively looked at
default is road tolling.  In the absence of other forms of private investment, this may become the only option if new infrastructure is to be created.  Specific schemes with clear objectives and with the most significant advantages could be considered, but a whol
defaultesale change to tolling of the motorway network along the lines operated in France, would not only increase costs significantly, but 
defaultwill
default have 
defaultconsequences for
default the rest of the network.  For ports, assessment
defaults
default 
defaultare already
default made of what contribution a port ca
defaultn make to a road or rail development linked to a port development.  So the ports industry itself is 
defaultpotentially 
defaultsubject to extra cost.  On
defaulte of the results of the recent Port Sector S
defaulttrategy 
defaultdocument 
defaultis an undertaking to review this arrangement.  
default&#xa0;
defaultSecondly
default, we believe that the Government should make much stronger efforts to ensure that the Trans European Network for transport (TEN-T) could also be used to fund road improvements.  Our understanding of the changes in the new TEN-T legislation is that apart fr
defaultom very specific road schemes strongly linked to environmental improvement, there 
defaultwill
default be no funding from TEN-T for roads 
defaultwhich
default instead will be allocated to inland waterways and rail projects.  Bearing in mind the 
